Gentrification in London

Introduction:

What is gentrification?:

For our analysis:

Data sources used:

This boxplot shows median incomes within all MSOAs across London, adjusted to 2020 prices.

Looking at each of ONS’ small area income estimates since 2011/12 together, we see average MSOA incomes appear fairly stable between 2011/12 and 2019/20.

At the time of this analysis, for two years in a row, London’s poverty rate had fallen to the lowest on record.

Yet at the same time other data in the London Poverty Profile pointed at soaring rents and a once in a generation cost of living crisis.

We wanted to better understand the mechanisms at work behind this drop in poverty, and wondered if a key factor could be low-income Londoners being priced out and replaced by wealthier residents. aka GENTRIFICATION
Gentrification is where an area rapidly changes its population, caused by an influx of wealthier households, which can cause a displacement of the previous population due to increasing unaffordability of rent and local services provided, resulting in the breakup of established communities and social networks.
The influx of more affluent residents to lower income areas, relative to the residents that were already there leading to the displacement of the previous population.

Identification of “gentrified” areas

  • Changes in income: Income estimates for small areas, 2010/12 - 2018/20, Middle Super Output Area level (MSOA), CPIH adjusted into 2020 prices (ONS)

Core Analysis

  • Population changes: Census 2021 compared to Census 2011 (ONS)

Further exploration/validation

  • House price changes for 2010 to 2023 (HM Land registry)
  • Changes in primary school applications between 2013/14 and 2023/24 (DfE)

Neighbourhood Incomes

The MSOA average income distributions are broadly similar across years. Starting with 2011/12,

then 2013/14,

2015/16,

2017/18,

and 2019/20.

However, if we look at 2011/12 and 2019/20 only, we see that there are some differences in the distribution of neighbourhood incomes.

Compared to 2011/12, there are more incomes in 2019/20 that centre towards the middle of the distribution.

and fewer incomes at the higher end of the distribution.

This means that, although median neighbourhood incomes are not very different between the two years, there are fewer neighbourhoods with very high average incomes in 2019/20, compared to 2011/12.

We can see this more clearly if we look at income levels for different income quinitles.

In 2011/12, the lowest income quintile had an average income of just under £30k

and the highest just under £50k.

By 2019/20, incomes had only slightly increased.

The 60% of MSOAs with the lowest incomes in 2011/12 had slightly higher median incomes in 2019/20.

The highest income MSOAs in 2011/12 actually saw a drop in their median incomes in 2019/20.

Here we have calculated the percentage difference between the 2011/12 and 2019/20 incomes, still split by the 2011/12 quintile groups

If we take a look at the distribution of those percentage changes in income, we see that there are interesting differences between the 2011/12 quintiles.

Specifically, when looking at quintiles 1 and 5, we see that the percentage changes in income between 2011/12 and 2019/20 are a lot higher for areas in the lowest income quintile in 2011/12 compared to areas in the highest income quintile in that year.

A lot of this around the middle of the distributions could be to do with increases to minimum/living wage rates

But quintile 1 also has a longer right tail, indicating very high average income increases in a small number of places.

Here are incomes in 2011/12 and 2019/20 plotted.

For the rest of the analysis we are going to concentrate on the areas belonging to quintile 1 in 2011/12.

This plot shows area incomes in 2011/12 and 2019/20 for those areas that were in the lowest income quintile in 2011/12, with the median incomes for each year annotated. We identified areas of interest to us as those that were below the median in 2011/12 and above the median in 2019/20.

And here they are on a map, coloured according to the average income change quadrant between 2011/12 and 2019/20.

The neighbourhoods in the Low to High quadrant in deep pink we will subsequently call the “Highest income rises”.

And here are the ‘biggest rises’ areas tallied by borough

Using census data inside these groups to examine the population differences as closely matched temporally to 2011/12 and 2019/20 as we can we see:

There are more people of lower managerial, administrative and professional occupations living in the areas with the highest income increases, compared to the rest of London. There are fewer people of routine occupations, long-term unemployed and students living in those areas compared to the rest of London.

One of the most remarkable drops is in children under 16 and there are also fewer young (16-29) and older (70+) people living in the areas with the biggest income increases. On the other hand, there are more people between 30 and 69 years living in those areas.

Worth noting here that primary school applications for 2023/24 have dropped in the whole of England, compared to 10 years ago.

This is particularly stark in central London - and these gentrified neighbourhoods appear to be contributing to this trend.

There is a also a drop in black people in those areas not seen in the other London categories.

White people are also dropping, but at a slightly lower level than the other London categories.

Other ethnic, Asian, and mixed or multiple ethnic backgrounds saw increases between censuses.

Increase in couples without children - higher than in the other London neighbourhoods.

Fewer mortgage owners, huge drop in social housing tenants and more people on private rents.

House prices in those areas were still lower than the rest of London but appear to have broken away from other areas in quintile 1 that did not see such big income increases.

When indexed to start at 2010 (=100), we see house prices in those areas increased at a much higher rate than the rest of London and the rest of the areas in quintile 1.

Questions left to answer!

Population Composition Changes

What does this mean for these areas?

  • A small number of neighbourhoods in London that had seen very large changes in average incomes
  • These areas were most commonly found in East London (Tower Hamlets, Newham), but also Brent, Southwark, and Haringey.
  • Changes in the housing stock of these places to the detriment of social housing in favour of private rental
  • Demographics shifts with decreasing proportions of children, black people
  • Increasing couples without children, Asian, and those from ‘other’ ethnic backgrounds
  • We see the composition of these areas changing, but are people being displaced?
  • If they are, where are they going?
  • And ultimately what does all of this mean for the future of London?
